Put a large #saucepan{} of water with a good pinch of @salt{pinch} on to boil for the pasta. Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1} into ½cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Finely chop the @chives{1/2} (or snip them with scissors).

Add the @rigatoni pasta{200%g} to your saucepan of boiling water. Cook until 'al dente', ~{10%minutes}.

> 'Al dente' literally translates as 'to the tooth'. It means there should be a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle of the pasta.

When cooked, drain in a #colander{}, reserving a little pasta water. Return the pasta to the saucepan off the heat to keep warm.

Meanwhile, heat a glug of @oil{glug} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the shallot. Cook gently, stirring frequently, until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Lower the heat and add the @king prawns{120} to the frying pan. Cook for ~{5%minutes}, turning every minute to make sure they cook evenly. When the prawns are pink, add the @vegetable stock powder{1/2} and @creme fraiche{150%g}. Cook for ~{2%minutes} more. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and a squeeze of @lemon{1/2}. Taste and add more seasoning if you like.

> The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque all the way through.

Rinse the @samphire{60%g} in a colander under cold water. Put another frying pan on medium heat. Add a glug of @olive oil{glug} and cook the samphire until hot and beginning to soften, ~{2%minutes}. It should retain some bite. Finish the samphire with the remaining lemon juice.

Combine the prawns and sauce with the pasta. Mix well and add a splash of the reserved pasta water to loosen it up if necessary. Add the chives and season with salt and black pepper. Taste and add more if needed. Serve the pasta in #bowls{} - avoid arguments by making sure the prawns are distributed with scrupulous fairness - then top with the samphire. Tuck in!